# Monitoring sync rule

The synthetic monitor died once already (Jun–Jul 2026: the tide/hourly-weather
refactor silently invalidated its assumptions and it emailed failures hourly
for 3+ weeks until it was ignored). These rules keep the monitor and backend
moving together. Design doc: `docs/synthetic-monitor-design.md`.

## If you add / remove / rename a scheduled job, or change a job's cadence

- Update the `JobSpec` in `shaka-api/.../monitoring/MonitoringConfig.kt`
  (or `registryExempt` for deliberately-unmonitored jobs). Cadences live ONLY
  there — `Application.kt` reads them via `scheduleRegisteredJob`.
- `MonitoringRegistryTest` fails the build if you don't. Do not "fix" the test
  by adding to `registryExempt` unless the job is genuinely exempt (cheap
  in-memory tick, cleanup, or admin-triggered).
- Watch the scheduled-name vs reporting-name trap: `solunar_vessel_prefetch`
  reports as `fishing_intel_prefetch`; `hourly_swell_wind_prefetch` reports as
  `hourly_swell_wind`.

## If you change how a data type is refreshed (e.g. age-based → horizon-based)

- Update the freshness derivation / horizon constants in `MonitoringConfig.kt`
  AND the corresponding section of `docs/synthetic-monitor-design.md`.
- Tide is NEVER age-based: `spot_cache` tide `fetchedAt` is months old by
  design. Only `spot_tide_series.generated_through` matters.

## If you change a health endpoint's shape or a user-journey endpoint

- Update `monitoring/journeys.json` (the shared shape contract) and, if
  assertion logic changes, `monitoring/probe.py` in the same change.
- The `probe-contract` CI job boots the API against
  `monitoring/fixtures/seed.sql` and runs the probe in `--local` mode; if your
  change 404s a journey or breaks its shape, that job failing is the system
  working — fix the contract, don't skip the job.
- If the response shape you changed is persisted in the seed fixture
  (hourly/tide/insights tables), update `monitoring/fixtures/seed.sql` too.

## If a change legitimately violates a probe recency anchor

`monitoring/journeys.json` contains probe-owned anchors the probe deliberately
does NOT read from backend config (e.g. T4: hourly `generatedAt` < 30h) —
they exist so backend threshold changes cannot self-ratify. If an architecture
change legitimately violates one (e.g. hourly fetch moves to a 3-day cadence),
update the anchor consciously in the same PR and say so in the commit message.

## Never

- Never hardcode a staleness threshold outside `MonitoringConfig.kt`.
- Never make the probe page on upstream-drift checks (Tier 2 is warn-only);
  bot-blocked responses from CI runners are `vantage-blocked`, not failures.
- Never set `DISABLE_SCHEDULED_JOBS` in production.
